<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-312-342  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 312 342.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  June 27 1989 v8 n12 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Laser printers get HPGL support in a cartridge. (Pacific DataProduct's Plotter in a Cartridge)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poor, Alfred.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Pacific Data Products Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Pacific Data Products Plotter in a Cartridge (Computer printeraccessory) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Software packagesLaser printersPlottersEmulationUtility ProgramsEvaluation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Laser Printers Get HPGL Support in a Cartridge It used to be that if youwanted your laser printer to emulate a plotter, you would have to buy onewith that capability built into its controller, or you had to run a separateutility that ate up valuable RAM or made you plot to disk.andP;  But now there'sanother way.andP;  Pacific Data Products has managed to put an HPGL-emulationprogram into a cartridge and in the process has created an incredibly fastway of printing graphics on a laser printer.andM;The $395 Plotter in a Cartridge fits into the left-hand slot of an HPLaserJet Series II or Canon LBP-8II.andP;  (It is not compatible with the HPLaserJet IID.)andP;  You can still use a font cartridge in the other slot; it'seven accessible when the plotter-emulation mod eis active.andP;  You can switchbetween plotter (HPGL) and printer (PCL) modes either by using a pair ofbatch files (included on a disk) or by pressing buttons on the front panel ofthe printer.andM;To find out just how much faster it is to print in the cartridge's plottermode than it is in the LaserJet's plain PCL mode, I decided to print a mapthat I created using Harvard Graphics.andP;  Printing at the highest resolution,the LaserJet took I minute and 56 seconds in laser printer mode, comparedwith a mere 31.7 seconds in plotter mode.andP;  Even more significant, I regainedcontrol of Harvard Graphics in less than 7 seconds under plotter mode,compared with having to wait more than a minute and a half under PCL mode.andO;That's quite a gain.andM;The Plotter in a Cartridge isn't just for people who use plotters--it's foranyone who prints graphs or charts or any other presentation materials andwishes to cut his or her printing time to a fraction of what it is currently.andO;This product is an excellent value.andM;List Price: Plotter in a Cartridge, $395.andP;  Requires: HP LaserJet Series II(with a minimum of 1.5MB RAM) or Canon LBP-8II laser printers.andP;  Pacific DataProducts, 6404 Nancy Ridge Dr., San Diego, CA 92121; (619) 552-0880.andO;</TEXT></DOC>